---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import BottomCTA from '../components/BottomCTA.astro';

const thesisSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'The Real Challenge in Retail Media',
  description: 'Why technically strong platforms lose deals they should win. The three operating realities that kill retail media partnerships.',
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Jaiah Kamara',
    jobTitle: 'Founder, Signal to Summit',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Signal to Summit',
    logo: {
      '@type': 'ImageObject',
      url: 'https://signaltosummit.com/images/logo-horizontal.png',
    },
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: {
    '@type': 'WebPage',
    '@id': 'https://signaltosummit.com/thesis',
  },
};
---

<PageLayout
  title="The Real Challenge in Retail Media"
  description="Why technically strong platforms lose deals they should win. The three operating realities that kill retail media partnerships — coalition dynamics, delivery scaling, and absorption capacity."
  pageType="article"
  schema={thesisSchema}
>
  {/* ── Section 4.1: HEADER ── */}
  <section class="py-20 md:py-28">
    <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-[45rem] px-6">
      <h1 class="text-summit-navy mb-4">
        The Real Challenge in Retail Media
      </h1>
      <p class="text-summit-navy/70 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Why technically strong platforms lose deals they should win.
      </p>
      <p class="text-summit-navy/50 text-sm">
        By Jaiah Kamara, Founder — Signal to Summit
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Section 4.2: THESIS VIDEO ── */}
  <section class="pb-16 md:pb-24">
    <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-[45rem] px-6">
      {/* Video — YouTube embed replaces this when URL is provided */}
      <div class="aspect-video bg-summit-navy rounded-lg flex items-center justify-center mb-4 overflow-hidden">
        <div class="text-center">
          <svg class="w-16 h-16 mx-auto text-white/30 mb-3" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/>
          </svg>
          <p class="text-white/40 text-sm">Video coming soon</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-summit-navy/50 text-sm">
        Watch the full thesis or read the written version below.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Section 4.3: WRITTEN THESIS ── */}
  <section class="pb-16 md:pb-24">
    <div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-[45rem] px-6">
      <article class="prose-thesis">
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          The retail media industry has a pattern that nobody talks about directly: technically strong platforms — the kind with real product capabilities, credible leadership, and genuine market demand — consistently lose deals they should win.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Not because the product fails. Not because the competition outspends them. But because the approach doesn't account for what's actually happening inside the retailer.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-12">
          After 15 years inside retail media — including seven years building measurement infrastructure at Best Buy Ads — I've watched this pattern play out hundreds of times. The same three operating realities kill partnerships before they have a chance to deliver value.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-summit-navy text-2xl font-bold mb-6">The First Misread: Coalition Dynamics</h2>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Platform providers approach retailers as if the person who says yes has the authority to make things happen. They don't. Inside a complex retail organization, the person who champions a partnership is rarely the person who controls implementation priority, data access, engineering bandwidth, or budget allocation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Deals don't die from product gaps. They die because the coalition required to move from agreement to implementation was never mapped, never built, and never maintained.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-12">
          The platform team thinks the deal is progressing because the champion is enthusiastic. Meanwhile, the people who actually need to do the work — the data team, the engineering team, the operations team — have never been engaged, have competing priorities, and may not even know this partnership exists.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-summit-navy text-2xl font-bold mb-6">The Second Misread: Delivery Scaling</h2>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Early implementations succeed because talented people throw themselves at the problem. A small team of heroes makes it work through personal relationships, manual workarounds, and sheer effort.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          Then the platform tries to scale. And every new customer requires the same heroics. Revenue grows linearly with headcount. Margins compress. The delivery model that felt like a competitive advantage at three customers becomes an operational ceiling at thirty.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-12">
          The platform has quietly become a manual service business wearing a technology company's clothes. Leadership knows something is wrong but frames it as a hiring problem or a process problem — when it's actually a delivery architecture problem that heroics papered over.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-summit-navy text-2xl font-bold mb-6">The Third Misread: Absorption Capacity</h2>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          The retailer says they're interested. They sign the contract. And then nothing moves.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          It's not a priority problem. The organization is operating under constraints the platform team consistently underestimates — bandwidth, data readiness, process maturity, organizational alignment. The retailer's ability to absorb new technology is not determined by interest or intent. It's determined by operational capacity that has nothing to do with the platform's product.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-12">
          The limiting factor isn't what they agreed to buy. It's what the platform's approach assumed they could absorb without support. This is the Usage Wall — the point where product capability exceeds organizational capacity to implement. Most platforms don't see it until they've already lost the partnership.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-summit-navy text-2xl font-bold mb-6">What Changes When You See It</h2>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          These three misreads aren't separate problems. They're interconnected patterns that compound each other. Coalition gaps create delivery complexity. Delivery complexity creates absorption bottlenecks. Absorption failures create coalition fatigue. The cycle accelerates until the partnership fails — and both sides walk away blaming the other.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7] mb-6">
          The platforms that break this cycle are the ones that learn to diagnose these patterns before they become fatal. They map coalitions before they pitch. They design delivery models before they scale. They assess absorption capacity before they assume implementation will happen on schedule.
        </p>
        <p class="text-summit-navy/90 text-lg leading-[1.7]">
          This isn't about being smarter. It's about seeing what's actually there — the operating reality inside the retailer that determines whether your partnership lives or dies. That reality is invisible from the outside. It's obvious from the inside.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Section 4.4: CTA ── */}
  <BottomCTA heading="If these patterns sound familiar, let's talk about what they look like in your situation." />
</PageLayout>
